In Qulice 0.18.19, If I have this code:
```java
    /**
     * constructor.
     * @param add {@link FieldAddition}
     * @param mul Field multiplication
     */
    public AbstractField(final FieldAddition<T> add,
        final FieldMultiplication<T> mul) {
        this.add = add;
        this.mult = mul;
    }
```
Qulice will complain with 2 violations:
* `First sentence in a comment should start with a capital letter (RegexpMultilineCheck)` because "constructor" starts with a lowercase letter
* `@param tag description should start with capital letter (RegexpSinglelineCheck)` because param add starts with a javadoc link

If I replace "constructor" with a javadoc link, for example:
```java
    /**
     * {@link FieldAddition}.
     * @param add {@link FieldAddition}
     * @param mul Field multiplication
     */
```
Qulice will not complain anymore for the first sentence in the comment. So making a javadoc link is fine for qulice as a capital letter starting, if it is in the comment, but not in the param tag description.

We should have consistency whether to consider a javadoc link a starting capital letter or not.
The better option is to consider it as a starting capital letter in all cases (so even as a `@param`/`@return` tag description), having links in javadoc is often handy.

Consider the following code:
```java
public interface ExternalInterface {
    void foo(String first, String second, String third, String fourth);
}

public final class MyImpl implements ExternalInterface {
    @Override
    public void foo(final String first, final String second, final String third, final String fourth) {
        // do nothing
    }
}
```

For MyImpl class the following warning is reported:

> More than 3 parameters (found 4). (ParameterNumberCheck)

However, the warning should not be triggered. The `foo` method is inherited hence overriden `foo` method in `MyImpl` must accept 4 parameters.
This is especially true when the external interface comes from 3rd party library and cannot be changed.

I believe ParameterNumberCheck should not be triggered for overriden methods, but only for method declarations.

