Qulice prohibits any static imports. It's good except unit tests which are all use assertions. My favourite assertions framework is AssertJ so I usually write something like:
```
import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;
import org.junit.Test;
public final class FooTest {
    @Test
    public void shouldReturnBar() {
        assertThat(new Foo().foo()).isEqualTo("bar");
    }
}
```
To please qulice I'd need to write Assertions.assertThat. Repeating Assertions class name only makes my code longer but it doesn't make it better.
- If someone is familiar with AssertJ then they know it's an AssertJ assertion just by looking at the code.
- If someone is not familiar with AssertJ then they would need to look at the documentation anyway
- It's true that reader of this code will need to check what class does the assertThat method come from. But writing Assertions.assertThat doesn't solve the problem because they will need to look what Assertions it is (JUnit, AssertJ or maybe even different)
- In today's world people often use IDEs instead of notepad or vim so it's quite easy to find what the class/method really is.

