If we have in our code a method that just calls a superclass method `NonStaticMethodCheck` complains.
Here is an example:

``` java
public class Parent {
    private int[] numbers;

    public Parent (final int... nums) {
        this.numbers= nums;
    }

    /**
     * Modifies a number.
     */
    public final void setCoor(final int pos, final int num) {
        this.numbers[pos] = num;
    }
}
```

``` java
public class Child {

    public Child (final int single) {
        super(single);
    }

    /**
     * Modifies a number.
     */
    public final void setNum(final int num) {
        super.setCoor(0, num);
    }
}
```

Qulice raises a `NonStaticMethodCheck` violation on the `setNum` method of the `Child` class.
I suggest that qulice treats `super` calls like `this` calls.

