Right now Qulice does not care about dot at the end of `@return` and `@param` Javadoc tags. According to #731 I propose to prohibit dot at the end of descriptions

Valid:

```
@param A string with contents. Cannot be null
@return True when empty, false otherwise
```

Invalid:

```
@param A string with contents. Cannot be null.
@return True when empty, false otherwise.
```

`Arrays.asList` with just a single argument wastes memory and is less performant than `Collections.singletonList`.
Let's create a check that will detect such cases.
Please first consider using PMD XPaths (like the ones we have in rules.xml) and only then try to create a code level (either Checkstyle or PMD check) check.

Please note that a valid case is:

``` java
byte[] array = new byte[3];
Arrays.asList(array);
```

but an invalid one is:

``` java
int data = 3;
Arrays.asList(data);
```

In task #659 a new rule was added to prohibit public static methods.
From other side in checkstyle rules we have NonStaticMethod that requires make method static if there are no references to this object. 
This is conflict of rules and may confuse developer. 
My proposition - modify NonStaticMethodCheck class to allow non static public methods if method has no references to this object. 
Example:
Valid 
`public int sum(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
 }`

Not valid - required to be static
`protected int sum(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
 }`

